**Why the schema delta exists.** BAML's class definitions describe shape using bare type names (`string`, `int`, `Foo[]`). The equivalent JSON Schema that OpenAI's structured-outputs / `tools=` / `response_format=` modes send on every call repeats type metadata as nested objects (`{"type": "object", "properties": {...}, "required": [...]}`). For a 5-field flat class, the JSON Schema is roughly 3–5× the byte size of the BAML definition. The savings scale with schema complexity and call volume.

**Reliability claim.** BAML's [Schema-Aligned Parsing (SAP) benchmark](https://www.boundaryml.com/blog/schema-aligned-parsing) reports higher schema-validity rates than OpenAI's native structured outputs on BFCL, using fewer tokens. {% if benchmark %}Our {{ benchmark.n_trials }}-trial benchmark above measures *prompt-format* deltas only; SAP's runtime parser benefits are not exercised here (would require routing through baml-py).{% else %}This report doesn't re-run that benchmark — but the migrated functions inherit SAP's behavior at runtime.{% endif %}

